n rights and democratisation. This changes - quite fundamentally - the EU's stance as an international actor and leads to questions about the nature of the European Union and how it perceives itself and is perceived by others.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCriseszEuropean Union countries. 0aCrisis managementzEuropean Union countries. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh  aEU.  aEuropean Union.  acrisis management.  acrisis response.  apeacebuilding.  asecurity.  astabilisation.1 aAla&apos;Aldeen, Dlawer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlockmans, Steven, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBøås, Mørten, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCissé, Abdoul Wahab, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDebuysere, Loes, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDrange, Bård, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFerhatovic, Enver, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGjerde, Kristian L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeinemann, Rebea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMac Ginty, Roger, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMac Ginty, Roger, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aOsland, Kari M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPeter, Mateja, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPeters, Ingo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rela